text: Recruitment success of anadromous fishes (striped bass, white perch and alosines) in
label: BODY

text: Maryland tributaries to Chesapeake Bay varies dramatically from year to year.
label: BODY

text: Additionally, the tributaries and their watersheds differ in the degree of human
label: BODY

text: development and impact that may affect reproductive success and productivity of
label: BODY

text: anadromous fishes.  In this project we undertook a retrospective analysis of data on
label: BODY

text: abundance, sizes, growth rates, and production of young-of-the-year (YOY)
label: BODY

text: anadromous fishes based on data from the Maryland Department of Natural Resources
label: BODY

text: (DNR) Juvenile Striped Bass Seine Survey that has been conducted since 1959.
label: BODY

text: Additionally, data on taxable structures located within three watersheds (Choptank,
label: BODY

text: Nanticoke, and Patuxent rivers) were analyzed as a proxy for level of human activity
label: BODY

text: and anthropogenic stress to evaluate potential effects of watershed development on
label: BODY

text: growth, distribution, and abundance of YOY anadromous fishes.  Significant increases
label: BODY

text: in the combined-taxa abundance and biomass of YOY anadromous fishes were
label: BODY

text: detected in the subestuaries that were sampled over the full time course of the DNR
label: BODY

text: surveys.  Abundances of the YOY alosines group declined significantly in the Choptank
label: BODY

text: River but increased in the Potomac River, attributable to increasing numbers of YOY
label: BODY

text: American shad in the Potomac.  Significant negative temporal trends in mean lengths
label: BODY

text: were detected for some YOY anadromous fish taxa.  Despite the apparent trends in
label: BODY

text: abundance and biomass, only a few of the trends in net production of anadromous
label: BODY

text: fishes were judged to be significant.  Shifts in spatial distribution of some YOY
label: BODY

text: anadromous fishes occurred during the 53-yr time series, with observed shifts in centers
label: BODY

text: of abundance being primarily down-estuary in some tributaries.  Principal components
label: BODY

text: analyses identified correlations and temporal patterns among water quality parameters,
label: BODY

text: freshwater flow, anadromous fish abundances and their centers of abundance.

text: Anadromous fishes, including striped bass, white perch, and alosines (American
label: BODY

text: shad, hickory shad, alewife, and blueback herring) are ecologically and economically
label: BODY

text: important in Chesapeake Bay.  Recruitment success of many anadromous fishes
label: BODY

text: exhibits more than 10-fold inter-annual variability in the Bay.  While the recruitment
label: BODY

text: levels of these fishes are correlated among Maryland’s Chesapeake Bay tributaries
label: BODY

text: (Kraus and Secor 2005; Wood and Austin 2009), the contribution of YOY recruits by
label: BODY

text: each tributary depends on numerous factors in addition to watershed size or areal
label: BODY

text: extent of available habitat.  Watersheds of each of the tributaries have experienced
label: BODY

text: different land use patterns and nutrient loading regimes that can affect carrying capacity
label: BODY

text: The proximity of many of the spawning and nursery grounds in Maryland to
label: BODY

text: urbanized areas makes these species especially sensitive to anthropogenic influences
label: BODY

text: (Schaaf et al. 1993; Uphoff 2008).  Analyses conducted by the Maryland Department of
label: BODY

text: Natural Resources (DNR) indicated negative relationships between the area of
label: BODY

text: impervious surface (IS) within a watershed, dissolved oxygen concentrations, and
label: BODY

text: abundance of juvenile anadromous fishes in several small Chesapeake Bay and
label: BODY

text: Potomac River tributaries (McGinty et al. 2006; Uphoff 2008; Uphoff et al. 2011).
label: BODY

text: Furthermore, the occurrences of white perch and yellow perch eggs, larvae, and adults
label: BODY

text: were diminished in the Bush River watershed in 2006 (IS coverage = 13%) relative to
label: BODY

text: 1973 (IS coverage = 9%) (Uphoff et al. 2007). Relationships among long-term trends in
label: BODY

text: nutrients and dissolved oxygen (Hagy et al. 2004; Kemp et al. 2005; Testa et al. 2008;
label: BODY

text: Prasad et al. 2010; Williams et al. 2010) and changes in land use and agricultural
label: BODY

text: practices in Chesapeake watersheds and the Bay have been documented (Cronin and
label: BODY

text: Vann 2003; Kemp et al. 2005; McGinty et al. 2006; Uphoff et al. 2011; Williams et al.
label: BODY

text: 2010). The research conducted by DNR on watersheds differing in IS coverage was
label: BODY

text: limited to data collected during a 3-year period.  We evaluated relationships among
label: BODY

text: long-term trends in abundance, growth, and production of young-of-the-year (YOY)
label: BODY

text: anadromous fishes that may facilitate management decisions on allocation of
label: BODY

text: • Quantify differences and trends in abundance, size, and growth rate among YOY
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: Chesapeake Bay and tributaries and relate to human habitation/land-use.
label: BODY

label: BODY

text: YOY anadromous fishes across tributaries and quantify temporal trends.
label: BODY

text: • Evaluate relationships between YOY fish, their zooplankton/benthos prey,
label: BODY

text: environmental variables, and land use metrics.

text: The Maryland Department of Natural Resources Juvenile Striped Bass Seine
label: BODY

text: measured YOY anadromous fishes in the Maryland tributaries of the Bay since 1957
label: BODY

text: (Figure 1).  The systems sampled since initiation of the survey include the Potomac
label: BODY

text: River, the Choptank River, the Nanticoke River, and the head of the Bay.  The Patuxent
label: BODY

text: River has been sampled since 1983.  There are multiple permanent and auxiliary
label: BODY

text: sampling sites in each system.  Each site is sampled once each month in July, August,
label: BODY

text: and September using a 30.5-m x 1.24-m bag-less beach seine of untreated 6.4-mm bar
label: BODY

text: mesh.  The time series is sufficiently long to capture shifts in abundance that appear to
label: BODY

text: be related to changes in freshwater flow patterns, other environmental variables, and
label: BODY

text: adult spawning stock biomasses.  These data were analyzed to compare trends and
label: BODY

text: differences in abundance, growth rates and biomass across tributaries under varying
label: BODY

text: environmental conditions.  With the exception of the Choptank River, only the sites
label: BODY

text: sampled continuously in each tributary since the beginning of the survey were used in
label: BODY

text: the analyses.  In the Choptank River, only one site was sampled continuously since the
label: BODY

text: beginning of the survey.  However, replacement sites were selected in close proximity
label: BODY

text: to the original sites and these were assumed to be representative of the respective

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: and patterns in the seine survey data.

label: BODY

text: An index of net production of each species from August to September was
label: BODY

text: calculated for each tributary by subtracting the mean relative biomass estimated in
label: BODY

text: Patterns or trends over years in the spatial distribution of each species were
label: BODY

text: evaluated by estimating the center of abundance of each species in each system for the
label: BODY

text: entire seine survey time series.  The center of abundance was calculated as a weighted
label: BODY

text: mean location (distance from the mouth of each tributary to each survey sampling site),
label: BODY

text: with the location weighted by the abundance of each species collected at each site.

text: There were several significant trends in the abundance of anadromous fishes
label: BODY

text: included in the analysis.  Herein, we first report on the abundances and biomasses of
label: BODY

text: combined groups of taxa and species and then on the individual species.  Striped bass
label: BODY

text: and white perch data were combined into a moronid group while the data for American
label: BODY

text: shad and the river herrings were combined into an alosine group.  Finally, the data for
label: BODY

text: all five species were combined into an anadromous group.
label: BODY

text: While there were periods of below-average abundance (i.e., density) for each of
label: BODY

text: the groups from 1957 to approximately 1960, and again in the 1980s, the abundances
label: BODY

text: of YOY anadromous fishes, most notably the moronid group, tended to exhibit positive
label: BODY

text: trends since the beginning of the time series, which is consistent with patterns reported
label: BODY

text: by Martino and Houde (2012) for striped bass and Wood and Austin (2009) for a suite of
label: BODY

text: species.  Conversely, with the exception of the Potomac River where YOY alosine
label: BODY

text: abundances increased, alosine abundances were declining throughout the time series
label: BODY

text: (Figure 2).  The trends in abundance were fairly consistent among tributaries and within
label: BODY

text: species groups, although slopes often were not statistically different from zero (Table 1).
label: BODY

text: Alosine abundance was more variable than the moronid or anadromous groups
label: BODY

text: because of frequent extreme high and low catches.  Trends in the anadromous group
label: BODY

text: abundance appear to be mostly driven by the moronid group, with absolute abundance
label: BODY

text: scaled upwards by large alosine catches. Negative trends in abundance across groups
label: BODY

text: within the Choptank River may be a consequence of the spatial distribution of survey
label: BODY

text: sites in this tributary, which included only one site in the tidal fresh region. This site was
label: BODY

text: excluded from our analysis because it was not sampled until 1984.
